    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-08T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-08T03:00:00-05:00" n="856"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d856">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6363 Manchuria/136: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-08T17:00:00+09:00"
                            >February 8, 1935—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 8—9:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>27. 1. On February 6, Kurusu<note n="74" xml:id="d856fn74">Saburo Kurusu,
                        director of the Commercial Affairs Bureau, Japanese Foreign Office.</note>
                    stated to Sansom of the British Embassy that the foreign oil companies were
                    still objecting to the monopoly as such and were not attempting to make business
                    arrangements within the monopoly. He believed this to be arguing in circles as
                    the monopoly plan would doubtless be carried out. He advised the foreign oil
                    companies to discuss the matter purely on a commercial basis leaving legal
                    aspects to be discussed by the Government.</p>
                <pb facs="0992" n="880" xml:id="pg_880"/>
                <p>2. Sansom replied that, although he did not know if the foreign oil companies had
                    reached a final decision, he had gathered from their representatives when he
                    last saw them that if the Manchurian authorities carried out the monopoly scheme
                    the foreign oil companies could see no alternative as a purely commercial
                    proposition except to dispose of their investments in Manchuria.</p>
                <p>3. The above reply of Sansom was prepared beforehand at a meeting of the special
                    representatives of the foreign oil interests.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
